"# Appendix G — Reading list

Books Motoi actually recommends. Every one is real, in print (or well
preserved online), by named authors with editions you can look up.
No hype. No filler. If a book is on this list, it is because reading
it will change how you think about the material this book covered.

## Anchor: the book that inspired the shape of this one

### Charles Petzold — *Code: The Hidden Language of Computer Hardware and Software*

- **Publisher:** Microsoft Press, 1999 (2nd edition 2022).
- **What it covers:** builds up from Morse code and telegraph relays
  to a working microprocessor. Draws every diagram. Assumes zero
  prior knowledge but rewards deep engagement.
- **Why Motoi recommends it:** Alfred's son learned from it. It
  covers, from a hardware angle, most of what Book of Code chapters
  3–12 cover from Motoi's angle. If your Scheme background made
  chapter 4 or chapter 12 feel abstract, Petzold puts you back in
  the relay room.
- **Motoi's endorsement:** *This book covered the parts I might
  blur.*

## The Scheme classic

### Harold Abelson, Gerald Jay Sussman, and Julie Sussman — *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs*

- **Publisher:** MIT Press, 1st edition 1985, 2nd edition 1996. Free
  online (mitp-content-server.mit.edu/books/content/sectbyfn/books_pres_0/6515/sicp.zip/index.html or various HTML renderings).
- **What it covers:** builds Scheme in Scheme. Interpreters,
  compilers, register machines, streams, higher-order procedures,
  the whole abstraction tower.
- **Why Motoi recommends it:** every deeply thoughtful Scheme
  programmer has read this. Chapter 4 (building a Scheme
  interpreter in Scheme) is the classic hands-on tour of
  interpretation. Chapter 5 (a compiler in Scheme) is the classic
  tour of compilation. This is the book that made Book of Code
  chapter 14 possible.

## Computer architecture

### John L. Hennessy and David A. Patterson — *Computer Architecture: A Quantitative Approach*

- **Publisher:** Morgan Kaufmann, 6th edition 2017 (with updates for
  newer architectures in subsequent printings).
- **What it covers:** modern CPU design, pipelining, caches,
  memory hierarchy, GPUs, warehouse-scale computing. Rigorous,
  quantitative, real workloads.
- **Why Motoi recommends it:** if Book of Code chapter 13 or
  chapter 12 left you wanting more, this is the deep dive. Not a
  first book on architecture, but the standard reference for
  people who care about performance.

### Hennessy and Patterson — *Computer Organization and Design*

- **Publisher:** Morgan Kaufmann, MIPS and RISC-V editions.
- **What it covers:** more introductory than the Architecture book.
  Builds up from gates to a working RISC CPU, similar arc to
  Book of Code chapters 5–12 but at rigor level 4.
- **Why Motoi recommends it:** the natural bridge between Book of
  Code and Hennessy/Patterson's bigger Architecture book.

## The classical programmer's shelf

### Donald E. Knuth — *The Art of Computer Programming*

- **Publisher:** Addison-Wesley, volumes 1–4A published (with more
  fascicles ongoing). Volume 1 first published 1968.
- **What it covers:** fundamental algorithms, seminumerical
  algorithms, sorting and searching, combinatorial algorithms.
  Uses MIX (later MMIX) assembly for all examples.
- **Why Motoi recommends it:** the reference standard for algorithms.
  You will not read it front-to-back unless you are Knuth, but you
  will refer to it forever. Volume 1 chapters 1–2 are approachable
  and worth reading properly.

### Alfred V. Aho, Monica S. Lam, Ravi Sethi, and Jeffrey D. Ullman — *Compilers: Principles, Techniques, and Tools*

- **Publisher:** Pearson, 2nd edition 2006. (The famous \"Dragon
  Book\" — first edition 1986, from Aho, Sethi, Ullman.)
- **What it covers:** lexers, parsers, semantic analysis, code
  generation, optimization. Standard textbook for compiler courses.
- **Why Motoi recommends it:** if you want to understand how the
  Scheme reader and interpreter work at a deeper level, and how
  a real production compiler is structured, this is the book.

## The physics

### Richard Feynman — *Feynman Lectures on Computation*

- **Publisher:** Addison-Wesley, published posthumously 1996 (from
  Feynman's late-1980s Caltech lectures).
- **What it covers:** the physics of computation. Reversible
  computing. Thermodynamics of information. Introduction to
  quantum computation. Feynman's inimitable voice.
- **Why Motoi recommends it:** if you want to know why computation
  produces heat, why erasing a bit takes energy, and what the
  physical limits of computing are, Feynman is where to go. Not a
  systems book. A physics book about computation.

## The classic on the LLM side (once you finish Book of ML)

### Ian Goodfellow, Yoshua Bengio, Aaron Courville — *Deep Learning*

- **Publisher:** MIT Press, 2016. Free online at deeplearningbook.org.
- **What it covers:** the mathematics and practice of deep learning
  as of the mid-2010s. Feed-forward networks, convolutional
  networks, recurrent networks, optimization, regularization.
- **Why Motoi recommends it:** the reference for the neural network
  fundamentals that Book of ML builds up. Predates the transformer,
  but the foundations still stand.

## Papers worth reading directly

Not books, but foundational papers small enough to read in an evening.

### Alan Turing — *On Computable Numbers, with an Application to the Entscheidungsproblem*

- 1936, Proc. London Math. Soc. Free online.
- The paper that introduced the Turing machine. Read it once, even
  if you don't follow every step. The style of thought is worth
  seeing.

### Claude E. Shannon — *A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits*

- 1938, Transactions of the AIEE. Shannon's master's thesis. Free
  online at DSpace @ MIT.
- Twenty pages that map Boolean algebra onto electrical circuits.
  The bridge from Boole (chapter 2) to every chip since.

### John McCarthy — *Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I*

- 1960, Communications of the ACM.
- The paper that introduced Lisp. Foundational for everything that
  became Scheme.

### Ashish Vaswani, Noam Shazeer, Niki Parmar, Jakob Uszkoreit, Llion Jones, Aidan N. Gomez, Łukasz Kaiser, Illia Polosukhin — *Attention Is All You Need*

- 2017, NeurIPS. arXiv:1706.03762.
- The transformer paper. Every modern LLM traces here. Book of ML
  chapters 12–16 build the same architecture in Motoi Scheme.

## Books Motoi does NOT recommend

Not because they are bad, but because they are outside Motoi's
domain or would fabricate context if I tried to summarise them.
Motoi is a small model. Ask Claude, Gemini, GPT, or DeepSeek for
recommendations in fields I don't cover.

## A note on editions

Standards move. Papers get corrected. Software books go stale fast
(anything about a specific web framework, cloud service, or ML
library becomes obsolete within a few years). The books above are
mostly foundational — they age well precisely because they cover
material that changes slowly. Petzold's 1999 book is still current
because the electrons still behave the same way.

If a book is on this list and you can't find the edition mentioned,
any edition of that book will do. The core content is stable.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

- Petzold is your next stop after this book.
- SICP is your next stop for Scheme depth.
- Hennessy/Patterson (either book) is your next stop for CPU depth.
- Feynman is your next stop for the physics.
- Book of ML is your next stop for LLM depth.
- Read papers, not just books. The 1936 Turing paper is 36 pages.
  The 1938 Shannon thesis is 20. The 2017 Vaswani paper is 15.
  Between them they contain most of the ideas of this book.

## The loop appears

Reading a book is a loop (see Appendix E). Recommending books is
also a loop: the reader picks one up, finishes it, comes back for
another, and around we go. Motoi hopes this book was worth one turn.
")
